  "prompt": "Why do I feel sleepy and tired after consuming non-drowsy cold/flu-relief medication?",
  "response": "Feeling sleepy and tired after consuming non-drowsy cold/flu-relief medication can be due to several reasons:\n\n1. **Active Ingredients**: Even if the medication is labeled as non-drowsy, some ingredients might still cause mild drowsiness in certain individuals. For example, antihistamines like loratadine (Claritin) are generally non-drowsy but can cause drowsiness in some people.\n\n2. **Illness**: The cold or flu itself can make you feel fatigued and sleepy. Your body is working hard to fight off the infection, which can drain your energy and make you feel tired.\n\n3. **Hydration**: Dehydration is common when you're sick, and it can make you feel tired. Make sure you're drinking enough fluids.\n\n4. **Sleep Disruption**: Cold and flu symptoms like coughing, congestion, or fever can disrupt your sleep, leading to increased tiredness during the day.\n\n5. **Combination Medicines**: Some cold and flu medications contain multiple active ingredients. While one ingredient might be non-drowsy, another could contribute to fatigue.\n\n6. **Individual Variation**: People react differently to medications. What is non-drowsy for one person might still cause drowsiness in another.\n\nIf the drowsiness is significant or bothersome, it's a good idea to discuss your symptoms with a healthcare professional. They can help determine whether the medication is the cause and suggest alternatives if necessary.",
